<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-751-302  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 751 302.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 13 1990 v7 n32 p38(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Open Text adds automatic indexing to document-management software.andO;(Open Text Systems Inc.'s Pat 3.4) (Connectivity )</TITLE><AUTHOR>Higgins, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The Canadian software publisher Open Text Systems Inc enhances itsdocument management software with full text search capabilities.andO;Pat 3.4 is a UNIX-based software package designed for documentmanagement on local area networks.andP;  New features, in addition tofull-text search and retrieval, are automatic indexing andimmediate updating of indices.andP;  Open Text Systems emphasizes Pat'sexceptional search techniques, which do not require special dataformats, and its speed.andP;  It is supposed to be able to retrieveinformation from data bases as large as six million words in twoseconds.andP;  It is priced at $10,000 per UNIX server, $40,000 per DECVAX server and $3,000 per 10 workstations.andP;  Lector, which providesa customizable user interface, and TTK, a data conversion utilityprogram, are available as an optional bundle for Pat users,beginning at $5,200.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Open Text Systems Inc. (product enhancement).andO;Product:   Pat 3.4 (Search software) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     EnhancementsDocument ProcessingSoftware Packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve HigginsandM;Open Text Systems Inc. is seeking to hasten the acceptance of its Unix-baseddocument-management software with an upgrade to the full-text search andretrieval program that forms the system's core.andM;The recently released upgrade to Open Text's text-retrieval software, calledPat, adds an automatic indexing feature that immediately records all changesto a document, ensuring that users can retrieve the most recent version of afile, according to David Terry, director of marketing for Open Text.andM;As with previous versions of Pat, version 3.4 works with Open Text's Lector,a user-customizable interface, and with TTK, a data-conversion utility thatallows users to display documents in their original formats.andM;While Pat lets users view only the portion of the document that contains theinformation they were searching for, Lector allows users to scroll throughentire documents, according to Terry.andM;The software trio, originally released in March, is designed to provide Unixwork groups with powerful document-archiving capabilities similar to thoseoffered by more established Unix-based packages such as Topic Inc.'s Verity.andM;The Open Text offering, however, surpasses its competitors because it enablesusers to initiate queries without using a particular data format, accordingto one user.andM;&quot;We think we have a really state-of-the-art search capability,&quot; said CharlesGoldstein, chief of the information technology branch at the National Libraryof Medicine's biomedical division in Bethesda, Md., which is using Pat.andP;  &quot;Noother system offered such a capability.&quot;andM;The software is designed to retrieve text from databases of 6 million wordsor less within two seconds, according to Open Text officials.andM;Pat is priced at about $10,000 per server for a version designed for a386-based server running Unix, or $40,000 for a version designed for aDigital Equipment Corp.andP;  VAX 9000 running Ultrix, according to Terry.andM;The price of Pat workstation software begins at about $3,000 for 10 users.andM;Pricing for Lector and TTK, which are sold together as options for Pat,begins at $5,200.andM;Open Text, located in Waterloo, Ontario, can be reached at (519) 746-8288.andO;</TEXT></DOC>